t-topping 16.7 cubic-feet. The 2020 Accord earned a Top Safety Pick award from IIHS, due in part to the inclusion of Honda Sensing safety technology as standard equipment. The package includes collision mitigation braking, road departure mitigation, lane keep assist, adaptive cruise control and traffic sign recognition. The Accord is available with three engine choices, one of which is a frugal hybrid system that delivers the best gas mileage. Fuel economy ranges from 26 to 48 mpg combined. For 2021, Honda makes Android Auto and Apple CarPlay available, dropped the manual transmission, freshened the grille, and replaced the mid-level EX trim with the Sport SE. The 2020 Accord earned a Top Safety Pick award from IIHS, due in part to the inclusion of Honda Sensing safety technology as standard equipment. The package includes collision mitigation braking, road departure mitigation, lane keep assist, adaptive cruise control and traffic sign recognition. The Accord is available with three engine choices, one of which is a frugal hybrid system that delivers the best gas mileage. Fuel economy ranges from 26 to 48 mpg combined. Pros & Cons Sleek styling and a clean interior design Hybrid offerings perform almost identically to conventional models Easy-to-use infotainment system The styling causes significant rear blind spots The trunk has a surprisingly narrow opening Road noise is louder than expected on some models Specs <best-of-specs :specs="specs" :show-mobile-ui="true"> Why We Picked It Pros & Cons Specs The Honda Accord is one of the most comfortable and usable sedans on the market, which translates into an excellent family experience. The Accord also sports 40.4 inches of rear legroom and 55 inches of rear hip room, enough for an adult or a full-size car seat to fit with ease. The Accord’s large rear door openings and gently sloping roof both help prevent bumped heads when loading ...Read More The Honda Accord is one of the most comfortable and usable sedans on the 