ains. Gas mileage ranges from 15 mpg combined for models equipped with a supercharged 6.2-liter V8 to 23 mpg combined for models with a 3.6-liter V6. No hybrid is offered (it’s a Charger, okay?). Updates for 2021 are minimal. Pros & Cons Big size means big, comfy interior Muscle car styling AWD expands capabilities Options drive up the price into V8 trim levels Big appetite for fuel in most situations Explaining to friends that it&#8217;s not a Charger Hellcat Specs <best-of-specs :specs="specs" :show-mobile-ui="true"> Why We Picked It Pros & Cons Specs The Dodge Charger is a larger car, which translates to a very roomy interior. The rear seat offers a whopping 56 inches of hip room, 40.1 inches of legroom (but edged out by Honda Accord) and 37 inches of headroom. Thanks to its size, the Charger’s 16.5 cubic feet of trunk space bests the other cars on this list. Performance enthusiasts also will appreciate its powertrain options ...Read More The Dodge Charger is a larger car, which translates to a very roomy interior. The rear seat offers a whopping 56 inches of hip room, 40.1 inches of legroom (but edged out by Honda Accord) and 37 inches of headroom. Thanks to its size, the Charger’s 16.5 cubic feet of trunk space bests the other cars on this list. Performance enthusiasts also will appreciate its powertrain options. The available supercharged Hemi V8 it can deliver 797 horsepower, but at a big price increase. The Charger’s safety scores include a Marginal rating for small overlap front driver-side crashworthiness and a Poor rating for its headlights from the IIHS. Though it is available with a host of advanced safety features, nearly all are only available as options packages or as standard equipment on higher trim levels. Fuel economy is a weak spot for the Charger, mostly due to its size and performance-oriented powertrains. Gas mileage ranges from 15 mpg combined for models equipped with a supercharged 6.2-liter V8 to 23 mpg combined for models with a 3.6-liter